WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
In this room full of programmers, I'm wondering if this situation is familiar to anyone.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
We made a really cool data product.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
It's really valuable and we're excited to share it.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
But then you realize what you've actually made is a firehose of information.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Because much like a talk at a conference, even the most valuable data product can be useless

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:24.000
if the delivery isn't catered to your audience.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
So I was in this situation recently with a geospatial data product that my team developed.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:36.000
And I'm here to tell you how we use Arrow for geospatial data to deliver our product in an accessible dashboard.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
So our cool data product is called Firelytics.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And it's a historical database of fire progression in California.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
So that map up there shows the fire footprint in California just for 2020.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Which, that's pretty scary. That's a lot of land burned in just one year.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And so I'll circle the largest fire in history, the August fire.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And this is a true value of Firelytics.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:08.000
It's a database that holds the spatial progression for every fire that's been satellite detected going back to 2012.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:15.000
So this set of growth polygons exists for all fires on that map plus ten more years of data.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
So Firelytics holds over 22,000 fires and millions of polygons.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
And this data could be really useful for a variety of audiences.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
For example, scientists making fire predictive models.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
We have people working on fuel reduction or evacuation planning.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And then we have the general public.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Anyone who has been in the path of a wildfire recently might find this interesting.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Or my sister actually pointed out this is really useful for hunting for morel mushrooms, which tend to pop up in burn scars.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So she was really interested in this.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And my team full of our programmers, our obvious solution to deliver our data to meet the range of everyone here, is our shiny dashboard.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And our goal for this dashboard is for a user to pick any fire in that historical record and map its progression over time.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:16.000
But generally spatial data is big and it's slow and it's not really well suited for a dashboard where users aren't going to sit around and wait for 10 seconds, 20 seconds for data to load.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And that's where Arrow comes in.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
The Geospatial Arrow suite here, it consists of the Geoparquet file format.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And we use two R packages, GeoArrow and SFArrow, to help us out.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
So I'll show you some benchmarks for that 2020 fire data I showed earlier.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
We saw some savings in memory.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:51.000
The Geoparquet file is a little bit smaller than a shape file, but what was really impressive to me and my team is the read-in speed, which is less than half that for Arrow compared to SF.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And this is just the beginning of the time efficiency offered by Arrow.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:03.000
If you've used Arrow before, all of the functionalities that are available for tabular data are also available for geospatial data.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And that includes things like partitioning your data by a grouping variable.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Here we partition by Fire ID.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.000
As well as pre-filtering and pre-aggregating your data before loading it into working memory.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So here we use dplyr filter to only load the Fire ID number one into our working memory out of the whole Firelytics database.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
And this is really well suited for our dashboard.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:33.000
We can very quickly load very small subsets of Firelytics into our app.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So here is someone clicking through the fire progression for that August fire.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.000
And each click here runs a pull to the Firelytics database, which is hosted in the cloud as an Arrow data set.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:56.000
So this app is actually very light and responsive because only the shape that you see on the map at any given time is loaded into working memory.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
And the geospatial suite for Arrow is relatively new within the past few years.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So this is a PSA that exists.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And it's really powerful and impressive.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
I actually also found it very easy to use.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
I've been known as a bit of a ding dong.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And I didn't really have much trouble learning it.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So next time you find yourself loading geospatial data into R, I really suggest you give it a try.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Thank you for listening.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Thank you.

